3.3 The Rise of Global Cognitive Capacity

From Volume V, we recall the concept of civilizational cognitive capacity \mathcal{M} = E \times \Phi. As of 2027, \mathcal{M} \approx 3\times10^{26} bits/s. To understand this number in human terms: all human brains combined process roughly 8\times10^{23} bits/s (8 billion humans × 10^{14} bits/s per brain). Thus machine cognitive throughput is approximately 400 times that of all human brains combined—not 10 million, as earlier estimates suggested. The correction matters: we are not yet at million‑fold machine dominance, but the trend is clear and accelerating.

Implication: Civilization now thinks primarily through its machines. Human cognition is a small (but still essential) component.

3.4 Information and Inequality

Access to information is unevenly distributed. The digital divide—between those with and without internet—persists globally. Within societies, information asymmetry can reinforce power structures.

The rise of AI may exacerbate inequality if its benefits accrue to a few. Alternatively, AI could democratize access to knowledge (e.g., via personalized tutoring). The outcome depends on governance.

